  "footnotes": [
    "Caucasian Albania / Arran (c.200 BCE–705 CE): an ancient Caucasian kingdom occupying roughly the territory of modern Azerbaijan; its native Caucasian Albanian language and people were gradually Armenianized or Turkified; Christianized in the 4th century; Arab conquest ended the kingdom in 705 though the Albanian Catholicosate survived under Armenian jurisdiction until 1836",
    "Shirvanshah Kingdom (799–1538): one of the most durable dynasties in the Caucasus, the Shirvanshah ruled northeastern Azerbaijan under successive Arab caliphal, Seljuk, Mongol, Timurid, and Turkmen overlords, maintaining local autonomy through skilled political maneuvering; the Safavid Shah Ismail I finally ended the dynasty and annexed Shirvan directly in 1538",
    "Eldiguzids / Atabegs of Azerbaijan (1136–1225): a Turkic dynasty that controlled the Arran region and much of northwestern Iran as nominal Seljuk vassals; at their height under Qizil Arslan they were the most powerful rulers in the region; destroyed by the Georgian Kingdom and then the Mongols",
    "Baku oil boom (1870s–1900s): after Russian annexation, Baku became one of the world's first industrial oil cities; by 1900 it produced roughly half the world's oil; Nobel and Rothschild family fortunes were built here; the industry's wealth and labor migration fueled early Azerbaijani national consciousness and ethnic tensions with Armenians",
    "Azerbaijan Democratic Republic (1918–1920): the first secular democratic republic in the Muslim world, it established Azerbaijani as the state language, extended suffrage to women, and created Baku University; persistent war with Armenia over Karabakh and Zangezur exhausted the state before Soviet conquest in April 1920",
    "Artsakh Republic (1991–2023): a de facto Armenian-majority state in the former Nagorno-Karabakh Autonomous Oblast declared independence during the Soviet collapse; survived two wars (1988–1994 Armenian victory; 2020 Azerbaijani victory regaining most territory); the remaining population fled after Azerbaijan's September 2023 military operation, ending the entity"
  ]
